04349nmm a2200517Ia 9781478059240DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780592407 a10.1515/97814780592402doi  a(DE-B1597)685452  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aR118b.B625 2024 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a610.1/4223/eng/202312111 aBriggs, Charles L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIncommunicable :bToward Communicative Justice in Health and Medicine /cCharles L. Briggs. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Philosophical Dialogues in Search of Incommunicability -- t1 The incommunicable menace lurking within locke’s charter for communicability -- t2 W. E. B. Du Bois: Incommunicability and/as the Veil -- t3 Frantz Fanon: Doctors, Tarzan, and the Colonial Inscription of Incommunicability -- t4 Georges Canguilhem and the clinical production of incommunicability -- tPart II How Incommunicability Shapes Entanglements of Language and Medicine -- t5 Biocommunicable labor and the production of incommunicability in “doctor-patient interaction” -- t6 Health communication: How In/communicabilities Jump Scale -- tInterlude: Social Movements and Incommunicability-Free Zones -- tPart III Communicable Contours of the COVID-19 Pandemic -- t7 Pandemic ecologies of knowledge: In Defense of COVID-19 Conspiracy Theories, Sort Of -- t8 Pandemic ecologies of care -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Incommunicable, Charles L. Briggs examines the long-standing presumptions that medical discourse translates easily across geographic, racial, and class boundaries. Bringing linguistic and medical anthropology into conversation with Black and decolonial theory, he theorizes the failure in health communication as incommunicability, which negatively affects all patients, doctors, and healthcare providers. Briggs draws on W. E. B. Du Bois and the work of three philosopher-physicians—John Locke, Frantz Fanon, and Georges Canguilhem—to show how cultural models of communication and health have historically racialized people of color as being incapable of communicating rationally and understanding biomedical concepts. He outlines incommunicability through a study of COVID-19 discourse, in which health professionals defined the disease based on scientific medical knowledge in ways that reduced varieties of nonprofessional knowledge about COVID-19 to “misinformation” and “conspiracy theories.” This dismissal of nonprofessional knowledge led to a failure of communication that eroded trust in medical expertise. Building on efforts by social movements and coalitions of health professionals and patients to craft more just and equitable futures, Briggs helps imagine health systems and healthcare discourses beyond the oppressive weight of communicability and the stigma of incommunicability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in medicine. 0aCommunication in public health. 0aLanguage and medicine. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aPhysician and patient. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059240?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059240/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles